GPF ORCID PROJECT

PRESENTATION BY DR. PENNINAH MUSANGI



1. Project Background

2. Project Activities

3. Lessons Learned

AGENDA



Project Background

• First cycle grantee for GPF
• Project Title: Empowering Librarians as ORCID 

ToTs
• Duration: One year (January – December 2023)
• Implementing organization: Kenya Libraries and 

Information services Consortium (KLISC)



Project 
Activities

• Librarians  have been trained as ORCID trainers of 
trainers;
• Formed COP where they share experiences and build 

one another on ORCID adoption among their respective 
institutions;
• Training materials (D-I-Y tutorials) have been developed 

and shared for future reference, self-learning and 
facilitated trainings;



Project Activities
• Directors of research from selected universities have 

been trained where:
• Best practices on ORCID adoption were shared;
• Members registered on ORCID and 
• Demonstrations on account updates done.

• Expected to provide advocacy and support to the 
librarians and ensure multiple stakeholder participation;
• Upgrade of IRs and integration with ORCID API – planned 

for November 2023.



Expected Outcomes

• Formation of ORCID community of practice (COPs) to 
advocate for ORCID adoption in Kenya;
• Organize ORCID trainings in KLISC member institutions;
• Directors of research to support librarians – multi-

stakeholder approach;
• Upgrading of IRs to Dspace ver. 7 and integrate with 

ORCID API.



Lessons Learned

• Different institutions are at different levels;
• Various PIDs exist, ORCID is central;
• Formation of ORCID COPs;
• Keeping ORCID up-to-date;
• Support postgraduate students in ORCID registration;
• Support authors in identifying their articles using ORCID;
• Consider an ORCID consortium for Kenya;
• QR codes on researcher cards.







